  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering penalties can include significant fines and prison time. Specific penalties depend on the circumstances, but generally involve:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences up to 20 years\n- Fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential additional charges related to underlying criminal activity\n\n2. Civil Penalties:\n- Substantial monetary penalties\n- Potential seizure of assets\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n\n3. Additional Consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential immigration consequences\n- Reputational damage\n\nThe severity of penalties typically depends on factors like:\n- Total amount of money laundered\n- Specific criminal statute violated\n- Prior criminal history\n- Role in the money laundering scheme\n\nThese penalties are primarily outlined in statutes like the Bank Secrecy Act and Money Laundering Control Act. Specific details can vary based on precise circumstances of the case.\n\nFor the most accurate and current information about a specific situation, I recommend consulting a qualified legal professional who can provide personalized guidance.",
